(151, 223, 'PCC2025159', 'Clarity by Dr Shivin, PW IAS, Toppers Talk etc.', 'No', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Sometimes. But I can control it while giving mocks. Not sure if it would be too much in the D-Day.', 'The amount of topics I have covered, I am able to correct most of the questions correctly. More comprehensive study with PYQ analysis needs to be done from my side. Much time I should invest in Polity as there are knowledge gap; previously I thought this as one of my strongest subjects.', 'Not being Confident enough to mark, Wrong Reading, Lack of focus while reading, conceptual clarity missing.', 'Not as such till now; I try to answer all the questions I am sure of in the first reading of the question paper and mark those I know but I am not confident enough to circle. In the second reading I try to think and apply my Intelligent guess for the remaining.', 1, 'Morning: 3 hours study (the subject that is the test Schedule) till I take bath and Lunch, then again 1.5-2 hours of study (Mostly notes making, current affairs), After taking a nap or walk/exercise again from 7.00pm-10.00pm study (scheduled test subject), From 11.00 pm-2.00am (Backlogs). CSAT weekly 2-3 times; which I need to improve.', '2025-02-23 21:53:00', '2025-02-23 21:53:00', NULL),
(152, 146, '20251098', 'ONLY IAS, Vajiram and Ravi, Rau\'s and Down To Earth', 'No', NULL, NULL, 5, 'Yes. One of the major reasons behind my last Prelims setback in 2020 was stress and anxiety. It was a COVID year with unprecedented struggles personally, that had affected my mindset adversely on the D-Day. I had also considered that attempt as do or die which led to further anxiety and failure.', 'The positive takeaways are: the value of planning, having a micro-goal oriented approach and the importance of a stable mental state.', 'The lack of guidance and maturity prevented me from doing my basics properly i.e understanding the need of the exam, analysing the syllabus and the PYQs, and the lack of institutional guidance.  Also, not maintaining good health is detrimental.', 'I have given one CSE Prelims exam, 5 years back, with a more naive mindset and much challenging times. The strategies I had opted back then were reading the newspaper regularly, giving mocks and regular revisions. But ignoring fundamentals led to my failure.', 1, 'Mornings (8am-12 pm) I dedicated to newspaper reading and CSAT, Afternoon (2-5pm) I either give a mock test or evaluate the tests given, followed by subject revision and PYQs from 6-11 pm with breaks in between.', '2025-02-23 22:27:16', '2025-02-23 22:27:16', NULL),
