(166, 47, 'OST2025192', 'STUDY IQ ,UPSC BY DR SHIVIN,DR UPSC,ONLY IAS,', 'NO', 'NOT APPLICABLE', 'NOT APPLICABLE', 0, 'Yes, I experienced anger and frustration when my exams didn’t go as planned, especially when test papers seemed more difficult than expected. It often led to feelings of self-doubt and comparisons with my peers, making me question my capabilities. However, I’m working on managing these emotions by focusing on my progress, learning from mistakes, and improving my mindset.', 'Mock tests and the UPSC Prelims have taught me valuable lessons in time management, handling pressure, and identifying my strengths and weaknesses. They’ve helped me understand exam patterns, improve my problem-solving skills, and build resilience. Each test, even when challenging, contributes to my growth and prepares me for the actual exam', 'After taking mock tests and the UPSC Prelims, I identified several mistakes, including:\r\n	1.	Poor Time Management: Spending too much time on difficult questions, reducing the time for easier ones.\r\n	2.	Overthinking and Self-Doubt: Second-guessing my answers, leading to unnecessary mistakes.\r\n	3.	Neglecting Certain Subjects: Focusing too much on strong areas while ignoring weaker topics.\r\n	4.	Inadequate Revision: Not revising thoroughly, causing difficulty in recalling facts during the test.\r\n	5.	Stress and Frustration: Allowing negative emotions to affect my performance.\r\n\r\nI’m now focusing on improving time management, building confidence, balancing subject preparation, and maintaining a calm mindset during tests.', 'Yes, I followed a specific strategy for mock tests and the UPSC Prelims:\r\n	1.	Time Management: I divided the exam time into sections, aiming to complete easier questions first and reserving time for tougher ones.\r\n	2.	Elimination Technique: For multiple-choice questions, I used the elimination method to narrow down options when unsure.\r\n	3.	Accuracy Over Attempts: I prioritized accuracy to minimize negative marking rather than attempting all questions.\r\n	4.	Analyzing Mistakes: After each mock test, I thoroughly analyzed my mistakes, identified patterns, and noted areas needing improvement.\r\n	5.	Stress Management: I practiced mock tests in a timed environment to reduce exam-day anxiety and improve focus.\r\n	6.	Revision Before Mocks: I revised key concepts before each test to boost confidence and performance.\r\n	7.	Consistency: I took mock tests regularly to track progress, build exam stamina, and develop a calm and composed mindset.\r\n\r\nThis approach helped me refine my performance and build confidence for the actual exam.', 1, 'Dont have a strict daily study schedule,as of now studying consistently the subject or month of current affairs exam going to be help next week and revising topics left out or last week test analysis,although  ,I do practice question sets daily', '2025-02-24 09:01:55', '2025-02-24 09:01:55', NULL),
